@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xi) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses a `match` as a VALUE in non-tail position (`let s = match …`).
-- The lowerer compiles `match` only in TAIL position (the `matchE` decision-spine); as the
-- RHS of a `let` it reaches `normComp`'s default and is refused. A value-position `match`
-- needs its whole decision-spine reified as a value — an IIFE wrapping the `If`/`Let`/`Fail`
-- spine `matchE` already builds (the same move `Cond` makes for a single binary branch,
-- generalized to the n-way match tree). The differential harness must report it
-- `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier — never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match` (tail); D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value (lowered to a
-- `Cond`; see compile_ifvalue_test). The frontier now sits at NON-TAIL `match` AS A VALUE.
-- This file uses one, so it still refuses; when value-position `match` lowers (a later D1
-- slice, reifying the spine as an IIFE), it flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let s = match 2
    | 0 -> "zero"
    | _ -> "other"
  println(s)
